The legal standpoint of that was due to the deritive nature of the work... similar to how Alfred Bester would get pissed at me if I wrote a story about the movement of humans to another evolutionary level guided by creatures from another planet (Childhood's End). It had nothing to do with people buying/selling their accounts, but instead making derivitive work. In addition, the hotbutton of &quot;Child Pornography&quot; got pushed by an overzealous parent who obviously believes that personal expression is utterly overruled by their own values.<br>
<br>
Oh, yeah, and verants resulting decision from that event was likely nothing more than a knee jerk reaction to try to stop &quot;Child porn&quot; and &quot;everquest&quot; from appearing in the same sentence at any given time. Makes great business practice, really. You wouldn't believe the number of people don't shop at a store that proudly says they support childmolesting. <br>
<br>
You know what else makes good business practice? Letting people pay for accounts that aren't really theirs. <br>
<br>
Hell, if Verant wanted to actually enforce the stuff they say are the 'rules' about transferring accounts, etc etc, then Makmut's own guildmates have written on numerous occasions that he is not the original, that he ebay'd but they didn't, etc etc. <br>
<br>
Before you say that they would need his own collaboration, they wouldn't. That's where the &quot;at our sole descretion&quot; part of the EULA comes in. Yep, they can ban at will, for no infraction if they so choose. They just don't by convention and in an effort to continue their domination of the market. <br>
<br>
Every ebay's 10 bucks is worth more to them than sticking to their 'rules'.<br>
<br>
/shrug <br>
